{"id":"1603.01997","submitter":"Bal\\'azs D\\'ora","authors":"Bal\\'azs D\\'ora, Rex Lundgren, Mark Selover, Frank Pollmann","title":"Momentum-space entanglement and Loschmidt echo in Luttinger liquids\n  after a quantum quench","comments":"7 pages, 7 figures","journal-ref":"Phys. Rev. Lett. 117, 010603 (2016)","doi":"10.1103/PhysRevLett.117.010603","report-no":null,"categories":"cond-mat.str-el cond-mat.quant-gas","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Luttinger liquids (LLs) arise by coupling left- and right-moving particles\nthrough interactions in one dimension. This most natural partitioning of LLs is\ninvestigated by the momentum-space entanglement after a quantum quench using\nanalytical and numerical methods. We show that the momentum-space entanglement\nspectrum of a LL possesses many universal features both in equilibrium and\nafter a quantum quench. The largest entanglement eigenvalue is identical to the\nLoschmidt echo, i.e. the overlap of the disentangled and final wavefunctions of\nthe system. The second largest eigenvalue is the overlap of the first excited\nstate of the disentangled system with zero total momentum and the final\nwavefunction. The entanglement gap is universal both in equilibrium and after a\nquantum quench. The momentum-space entanglement entropy is always extensive and\nsaturates fast to a time independent value after the quench, in sharp contrast\nto a spatial bipartitioning.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 7 Mar 2016 10:44:59 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Wed, 15 Jun 2016 19:40:06 GMT"}],"update_date":"2016-07-01"}
